# Scripts here run on Linux and macOS, where a CR is not whitespace: it becomes
# part of the shebang (`env: 'bash\r': No such file or directory`) and of every
# value the script reads. Git Bash on Windows tolerates CRLF, so a CRLF commit
# looks fine to the contributor who makes it and breaks for everyone else.
#
# Without this file, LF in the repo depends on each contributor having
# core.autocrlf=true. One clone with autocrlf=false and a CRLF-writing editor is
# enough to commit a CRLF blob. These rules normalize on the way in regardless
# of local config, so that cannot happen.
#
# .ps1 is included because setup.ps1 carries a `#!/usr/bin/env pwsh` shebang and
# is meant to be executable on Linux/macOS too; PowerShell reads LF on Windows.
*.sh  text eol=lf
*.ps1 text eol=lf

# leak-gate.allow is read as anchored grep patterns; a stray CR corrupts the regex ($\r never
# matches) and would SILENTLY break the README operator-credit exception. Force LF like above.
.harness/leak-gate.allow text eol=lf
